# A Notification System That Respects Attention

The grain of this problem is **asymmetry** вҖ” the cost of a bad notification is felt immediately and viscerally, but the value of a good one is often invisible (you just... knew the right thing at the right time). Most systems optimize for delivery. This one needs to optimize for *silence*, and treat every interruption as a withdrawal from a finite account.

---

## The Core Insight: Notifications Have Temperature

Not all information is urgent, but urgency isn't the only axis that matters. A notification's real value lives at the intersection of three things:

| Dimension | What it means | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Relevance** | Does this matter to *this person* right now? | A deploy failure matters to the on-call engineer, not the PM |
| **Timeliness** | Does knowing *now* vs. *later* change what they'd do? | "Your flight gate changed" вҶ’ yes. "Weekly digest" вҶ’ no |
| **Agency** | Can they act on this? | "Server down" when they have SSH access вҶ’ yes. When they don't вҶ’ just anxiety |

A notification that scores high on all three is **warm** вҖ” it feels like a tap on the shoulder from a friend. One that misses on any axis is **cold** вҖ” it feels like spam, even if it's technically "important."

Most systems only model urgency (a blunt proxy for timeliness) and ignore relevance and agency entirely.

---

